<section xml:id="section-graphically-solving-equations-and-inequalities">
  <title>Graphically Solving Equations and Inequalities</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-solve-equations-and-inequalities-graphically" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction permid="svB">
    <p>
      It is possible to solve equations and inequalities simply by reading a graph well.
      In this section, we take that approach to solving equations.
    </p>

    <figure permid="eNI">
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="" />
    </figure>

  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Equations Using a Graph</title>
    <p>
      To <em>algebraically</em> solve an equation like <m>-0.01x^2+0.7x-18=-0.04x^2-3.6x+32</m>,
      we'd start by rearranging terms so that we could apply the quadratic formula.
      That would be a lot of pencil-and-paper work, and a lot of opportunity to make human errors.
      An alternative is to <em>graphically</em>
      solve this equation. We start by graphing both
      <md>
        <mrow>y\amp=-0.01x^2+0.7x-18\amp\amp\text{and}\amp y\amp=-0.04x^2-3.6x+32</mrow>
      </md>.
      It happens that we learned how to graph equations like these by hand
      in <xref ref="section-graphing-quadratic-expressions">Section</xref>,
      but we will <q>cheat</q> in this section and use graphing technology to just make the graphs for us.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equation <m>-0.01x^2+0.7x-18=-0.04x^2-3.6x+32</m> graphically.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <figure>
            <caption><m>y=-0.01x^2+0.7x-18</m> and <m>y=-0.04x^2-3.6x+32</m></caption>
            <image>
              <description></description>
              <latex-image>
                  <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-60,xmax=100,
                      ymin=-40,ymax=60,
                      xtick={-40,-20,...,80},
                      minor xtick={-50,-40,...,90},
                      ytick={-30,-20,...,50},
                      minor ytick={-30,-20,...,50},
                      clip=false,
                          ]
                          \addplot+[domain=-48.815:100,samples=100] {-0.01*(x-90)*(x+20)};
                          \addplot+[domain=-2.17:92.17,samples=100] {-0.04*(x-10)*(x-80)};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(22.46,28.677)} node[above right]{$(22.46,28.677)$};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(74.207,14.878)} node[below left]{$(74.207,14.878)$};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>

          <stack>
            <p>
              There are two points of intersection where the curves cross each other:
              <m>(22.46,28.677)</m> and <m>(74.207,14.878)</m>.
              Each one of them tells you a solution to the equation we started with.
              The point <m>(22.46,28.677)</m> means that when <m>x</m> is about <m>22.46</m>,
              both <m>-0.01x^2+0.7x-18</m> and <m>-0.04x^2-3.6x+32</m> work out to the same result.
              That result is about <m>28.677</m>, but that really doesn't matter right now.
              Its the <m>x</m>-value, about <m>22.46</m>, that matters.
              That is one solution to the equation.
            </p>
            <p>
              The second point of intersection similarly shows us that <m>74.207</m> is another approximate solution.
              We can conclude that the solution set to the equation is approximately <m>\{22.46,74.207\}</m>.
            </p>
          </stack>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graphically solve the equation <m>-0.01(x-90)(x+20)=25</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Start by graphing two curves on the same plot: <m>y=\text{left}</m> and <m>y=\text{right}</m>.
          Specifically for this example, <m>y=-0.01(x-90)(x+20)</m> and <m>y=25</m>.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <figure>
            <caption><m>y=-0.01(x-90)(x+20)</m> and <m>y=25</m></caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <description></description>
              <latex-image>
                  <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[xmin=-60,xmax=100,
                      ymin=-40,ymax=60,
                      xtick={-40,-20,...,80},
                      minor xtick={-50,-40,...,90},
                      ytick={-30,-20,...,50},
                      minor ytick={-30,-20,...,50},
                      clip=false,
                          ]
                          \addplot+[domain=-48.815:100,samples=100] {-0.01*(x-90)*(x+20)};
                          \addplot+[domain=-60:100] {25};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(12.807,25)} node[above right, rotate=20]{$(12.807,25)$};
                          \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates {(57.913,25)} node[above right, rotate=20]{$(57.913,25)$};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>

          <p>
            The points of intersection are
            <m>(12.807,25)</m> and <m>(57.913,25)</m>,
            which tells us that the solutions are approximately <m>12.807</m> and <m>57.913</m>.
            The solution set is approximately <m>\{12.807, 57.913\}</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      One excellent thing about solving equations graphically is that it doesn't really matter what <q>kind</q> of equation it is.
      The equation can have mathematics in it that you haven't specifically studied,
      but as long as something (like a computer or your teacher) provides you with the graphs,
      you can still solve the equation.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graphically solve the equation <m>\lvert x+5\rvert=\frac{1}{x+1}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If you've only been learning algebra from this textbook, this equation has some unfamiliar bits and pieces.
          The vertical bars in <m>\lvert x+5\rvert</m> represent the basic math concept of absolute value,
          which you can brush up on in <xref ref="section-absolute-value-and-square-root">Appendix</xref>.
          On the other side of the equation there is the expression <m>\frac{1}{x+1}</m>,
          with a variable in the denominator. This textbook hasn't discussed such things yet.
        </p>
        <p>
          Even though we don't yet have general knowledge for these kinds of math expressions and their graphs,
          we can still trust some source to provide the graphs for us.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <figure>
            <caption><m>y=\lvert x+5\rvert</m> and <m>y=\frac{1}{x+1}</m></caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <description></description>
              <latex-image>
                  <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                      \begin{axis}[]
                          \addplot+[] coordinates {(-7,2) (-5,0) (2,7)} node[below right] {$y=\lvert x+5\rvert$};
                          \addplot+[variable=u, domain=-1.94:2.07] ({e^u - 1}, {e^-u}) node[above left] {$y=\frac{1}{x+1}$};
                          \addplot[secondcurve, variable=u, domain=-1.94:1.79] ({-e^u - 1}, {-e^-u});
                          \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-0.7639,4.236)} node[left] {$(-0.7639,4.236)$};
                      \end{axis}
                  \end{tikzpicture}
                  ]]>
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>

          <p>
            It appears there is only one point of intersection at about <m>(-0.7639,4.236)</m>.
            So the solution set is approximately <m>\{-0.7639\}</m>.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      If we are solving graphically and something is already providing you with the graph,
      it's not even necessary to have math expressions for the two curves.
    </p>

    <example>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <stack>
          <p>
            In <xref ref="figure-solve-graphically-no-equations">Figure</xref>,
            there are two curves plotted. The horizontal axis represents years,
            one curve represents the population of California,
            and the other curve represents the population of New York.
            In what year did the population of California equal the population of New York?
